  "doc_id": "12536",
  "text": "Structural plasticity in the superior colliculus appears to terminate during the period when we have documented significant changes in NMDA receptors. In rats, retinocollicular axons can fill in an induced scotoma until P10 (L und and L und, 1976) , and corticocollicular inputs can fill retinal scotomas until P15 [CITATION_1] . Spontaneous activity and NMDA receptor function have been implicated in collicular synaptogenesis before pattern vision by evidence that TTX disrupts the elimination of the ipsilateral retinocollicular projection [CITATION_2] , that early temporally patterned spontaneous activity occurs in the fetus of many species [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , and that both retinocollicular map refinement and several indices of normal synaptic differentiation [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] in the rat can be stalled by chronic NMDA receptor antagonism begun at P0. The differentiation of inhibitory transmission after eye opening that we have observed may represent an additional mechanism for controlling both excitation and the potential for structural change in this neuropil.",
